04769nam a22007695i 9780231548458DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018043952  a97802315484587 a10.7312/ales189662doi  a(DE-B1597)526806  a(OCoLC)1056201967  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPG3478.L443bA2 2019 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a891.73/442231 aAleshkovsky, Yuz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNikolai Nikolaevich and Camouflage :bTwo Novels /cYuz Aleshkovsky; ed. by Susanne Fusso. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRussian Library00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tNIKOLAI NIKOLAEVICH. A Science Fiction Story -- tCAMOUFLAGE. A Medical History -- tNOTES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong contemporary Russian writers, Yuz Aleshkovsky stands out for his vivid imagination, his mixing of realism and fantasy, and his virtuosic use of the rich tradition of Russian obscene language. These two novels, written in the 1970s, display Aleshkovsky’s linguistic gifts and keen observations of Soviet life.Nikolai Nikolaevich begins when its titular hero, a pickpocket by trade, is released from prison after World War II and finds a job in a Moscow biological laboratory. Starting out as a kind of janitor, he is soon recruited to provide sperm for strange experiments intended to create life in the Andromeda galaxy. The hero finds himself at the center of the 1948 purge of biological science in the Soviet Union, in a transgressive tale that joins science fiction (and science fact) with gulag slang and a love story. The protagonist and narrator of Camouflage is an alcoholic who claims that he and his gang of friends are just one part of a vast camouflaging operation organized by the Party to hide the Soviet Union’s underground military-industrial complex from the CIA’s spy satellites. As they pass their time on the streets and share their alcohol-inspired fantasies, they see the stark reality of the Cold War in Russia in the late seventies. Nikolai Nikolaevich and Camouflage introduces English-speaking readers to a master of the comic first-person narrative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aFusso, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFusso, Susanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWhite, Duffield.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz978311061036908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/ales1896640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231548458423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231548458.jpg  a978-3-11-061036-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065195-9  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2019  aZDB-